# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Krew Recruiter — Environment Variables Template
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Copy this file to .env (which is .gitignored) and fill in real values:
#
#   cp .env.example .env
#
# In production these should be set in the DigitalOcean App Platform
# dashboard (Settings → Components → krew-recruter → Environment
# Variables), NOT committed to the repo. The .do/app.yaml file in this
# repo only contains non-sensitive values like PORT and PUBLIC_URL.
#
# This file documents EVERY environment variable the codebase reads,
# so a fresh developer / new environment knows what's needed without
# having to grep `process.env.` themselves.
#
# To verify this list is still complete:
#   grep -rh 'process\.env\.' server client shared \
#     | grep -oE 'process\.env\.[A-Z_]+' | sort -u
#
# Severity legend (used in comments below):
#   [CRITICAL]  Leaking this owns your production service
#   [HIGH]      Leaking this enables financial / data harm
#   [MEDIUM]    Leaking this is bad but recoverable
#   [LOW]       Operational config, not a secret
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────


# ─── Core ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# [LOW] Node environment. Affects Vite dev server vs static file
# serving in server/index.ts, secure cookie flag in customAuth.ts,
# and various log behavior. Use "development" locally, "production"
# in DO.
NODE_ENV=development

# [LOW] HTTP port the express server listens on. Defaults to 3000 if
# unset. .do/app.yaml sets this to 8080 in production to match
# DigitalOcean App Platform's expected ingress port.
PORT=3000

# [LOW] Canonical public URL of the deployed app. Used by server-side
# code that builds outbound links — most importantly the apply URL
# embedded in Meta ad creatives by server/services/meta-ads.ts. If
# unset, the code falls back to the hardcoded value in
# server/routes.ts:3993. Now version-controlled in .do/app.yaml for
# production; this entry is for local dev / staging.
PUBLIC_URL=http://localhost:3000


# ─── Database ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# [CRITICAL] Postgres connection string. Anyone with this owns the
# entire database — all user data, all org data, all encrypted
# secrets in the platform_settings table. server/db.ts requires this
# to start with "postgresql://".
#
# Rotation procedure (DigitalOcean Managed Postgres):
#   1. Create a new database user in the DO dashboard with the same
#      privileges as the current one
#   2. Update DATABASE_URL in DO env vars to use the new user
#   3. Restart the app and verify connectivity
#   4. Drop the old user
DATABASE_URL=postgresql://USER:PASSWORD@HOST:25060/DBNAME?sslmode=require

# [LOW] Alternative name for DATABASE_URL — see server/db.ts. The
# code accepts either; do not set both. Prefer DATABASE_URL.
# DB_URL=

# [HIGH] Disables TLS certificate verification GLOBALLY when set to
# "0". Sometimes needed for DigitalOcean Managed Postgres if the
# self-signed cert chain isn't trusted by the runtime, but using it
# disables cert verification for ALL outbound HTTPS calls (Stripe,
# Anthropic, Meta, etc.) — meaning a man-in-the-middle on your egress
# could intercept every API call. Prefer fixing the cert chain
# (e.g. installing the DO CA bundle) over enabling this flag. Leave
# unset in production.
# NODE_TLS_REJECT_UNAUTHORIZED=0


# ─── Auth / Sessions ───────────────────────────────────────────────

# [CRITICAL] Express-session signing secret. Rotating this invalidates
# all active sessions and forces every user to log in again. Use a
# long random string — at least 32 bytes of entropy.
#
# Generate with:
#   openssl rand -base64 48
SESSION_SECRET=replace-me-with-openssl-rand-base64-48

# [CRITICAL] JWT signing secret. Used by /api/auth/login and
# /api/auth/register to issue API tokens; verified by jwtAuth.ts and
# the admin check at routes.ts:2665, 2710. Rotating invalidates all
# active JWTs immediately.
#
# Generate with:
#   openssl rand -base64 48
#
# WARNING — KNOWN BUG (audit finding, not yet fixed):
# server/customAuth.ts:143 and server/routes.ts:2665, 2710 fall back
# to the hardcoded literal "krew-jwt-secret" if this env var is unset
# at runtime. That fallback is a CRITICAL auth bypass — anyone who
# reads the source can mint valid tokens for any user. JWT_SECRET
# MUST be set in every environment until that fallback is removed.
JWT_SECRET=replace-me-with-openssl-rand-base64-48

# [LOW] Comma-separated list of email addresses granted super-admin
# privileges in the admin dashboard. Not a secret, just access
# control configuration. Read at server/routes.ts:2604.
SUPER_ADMIN_EMAILS=admin@example.com,owner@example.com


# ─── Stripe (Payments) ─────────────────────────────────────────────

# [CRITICAL] Stripe API secret key. Anyone with this can charge cards,
# refund payments, view customer data, manipulate subscriptions, and
# create connected accounts. ALWAYS use sk_test_... in dev; only use
# sk_live_... in production.
#
# Rotation procedure:
#   1. Stripe Dashboard → Developers → API keys → "Roll secret key"
#   2. Update STRIPE_SECRET_KEY everywhere immediately
#   3. The old key has a configurable grace period — set it to the
#      shortest you can tolerate (default is 12 hours)
STRIPE_SECRET_KEY=sk_test_replace_me

# [LOW] Stripe publishable key. Sent to the browser for Stripe.js
# initialization. NOT a secret — exposing this in client code is
# expected. Listed here only for completeness.
STRIPE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY=pk_test_replace_me

# [HIGH] Stripe webhook signing secret. Used at server/index.ts:35
# to verify the signature on incoming webhook events. If leaked, an
# attacker can forge events (e.g. fake "subscription paid" or
# "checkout completed") which would update tenant billing status
# without any real payment.
#
# Rotation procedure:
#   1. Stripe Dashboard → Developers → Webhooks → select endpoint
#   2. Click "Roll secret"
#   3. Update STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET in DO env vars before the old
#      secret stops working (Stripe sends events signed with both
#      secrets during the rollover window)
STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET=whsec_replace_me


# ─── Anthropic (Claude API) ────────────────────────────────────────

# [HIGH] Anthropic API key. Used at server/services/job-filter.ts:62
# and server/campaignRoutes.ts:916, 987 for ad copy generation and
# job posting extraction from URLs. If leaked, an attacker can rack
# up usage charges against your account — Anthropic bills per-token
# and there's no per-key spending cap.
#
# Rotation procedure:
#   1. console.anthropic.com → API Keys
#   2. Generate a new key with the same workspace permissions
#   3. Update ANTHROPIC_API_KEY in DO env vars + restart
#   4. Revoke the old key
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-api03-replace_me


# ─── Platform Settings Encryption ──────────────────────────────────

# [CRITICAL] Passphrase used to derive (via scrypt with the constant
# salt "krew-platform-salt") the AES-256-GCM key that encrypts
# sensitive values stored in the platform_settings table. Currently
# protects: meta_access_token, meta_app_secret. See
# server/services/platformSettings.ts.
#
# Generate with:
#   openssl rand -base64 48
#
# IMPORTANT: if you change this value, the next app restart will
# fail to decrypt every encrypted row in platform_settings and Meta
# ads will break. ALWAYS run the rotation script first:
#
#   OLD_PLATFORM_SETTINGS_ENCRYPTION_KEY='<current value>' \
#   NEW_PLATFORM_SETTINGS_ENCRYPTION_KEY='<new value>' \
#   tsx server/scripts/rotatePlatformSettingsKey.ts --apply
#
# (See the script header for the full procedure including dry-run
# verification and backup file handling.)
#
# WARNING: the value "krew-platform-enc-key-change-me-32" originally
# shipped in this codebase was a placeholder. If your production
# environment is still using that string, encrypted Meta tokens are
# protected by a publicly-known key — rotate immediately.
PLATFORM_SETTINGS_ENCRYPTION_KEY=replace-me-with-openssl-rand-base64-48


# ─── Optional: Adzuna (External Job Aggregator) ────────────────────

# [MEDIUM] Adzuna API credentials. Optional — only required if you
# enable the external job board aggregation feature
# (server/services/adzuna.ts, server/services/job-aggregator.ts).
# Get keys at developer.adzuna.com.
# ADZUNA_APP_ID=
# ADZUNA_APP_KEY=


# ─── Replit Legacy (no longer used on DO) ──────────────────────────

# These are referenced by code paths in server/replit_integrations/*
# that were used when this app ran on Replit. They are not used in
# the current DigitalOcean deployment. Listed here only so a grep of
# `process.env.` returns a complete picture. Do NOT set in production.
# REPL_ID=
# ISSUER_URL=
# PUBLIC_OBJECT_SEARCH_PATHS=
# PRIVATE_OBJECT_DIR=
